unity of Irish American, Italian American, and Puerto Rican families is shown with honesty and insight.Racioppo’s 128 photographs are paired with essays from journalist Tom Robbins and art critic and curator Julia Van Haaften. Taken together, the images and words of Brooklyn Before return us to pre-gentrification Brooklyn and immerse us in a community defined by work, family, and ethnic ties.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aStreet photography. 4aNew York History. 4aPhotography. 4aUrban Studies. 7aPhotography / Individual Photographers / Monographs.2bisacsh  aBrooklyn, Change, Neighborhood, Family, Religion, Working Class, Blue Collar.1 aHaaften, Julia Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRacioppo, Larry.1 aRobbins, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobbins, Tom.1 aVan Haaften, Julia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172677440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501726774423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501726774.jpg  a978-3-11-060655-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles